'''Matsue Gokoku Shrine''' (松江護國神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Gokoku Shrine|ja|護国神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) located on the site of {{ill|Matsue Castle|ja|松江城|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Matsue|ja|松江市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|ja|島根県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Overview ==
The shrine enshrines over 22,000 spirits of war dead from the former {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|Izumo Province|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Oki Province|ja|Oki Province|qq=draft|qq=draft}} who died in national crises after the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Another Gokoku Shrine in the prefecture is {{ill|Hamada Gokoku Shrine|ja|濱田護國神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

In {{ill|Showa|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 10 ({{ill|1935|ja|1935th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), the Shimane Prefecture Shokonsha Construction Support Association was organized. In Showa 14 ({{ill|1939|ja|1939th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), it was established and enshrined as Matsue Shokonsha in March, but in April of the same year, due to the reformation of the Shokonsha system, it became Matsue Gokoku Shrine. After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was temporarily called Shimane Shrine, but after Japan's sovereignty was restored, the original name was reinstated in Showa 28 ({{ill|1953|ja|1953rd year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).

On May 10, Showa 40 ({{ill|1965|ja|1965th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), {{ill|Emperor Showa|ja|昭和天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Empress Kojun|ja|香淳皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft}} visited the shrine during the 16th {{ill|National Tree Planting festival|ja|全国植樹祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which was held in the prefecture<ref>{{Cite book |和書 |author={{ill|Takeuchi Tadanori|ja|原武史|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |title=昭和天皇御召列車全記録 |publisher=新潮社 |year=2016-09-30 |page=129 |isbn=978-4-10-320523-4}}</ref>.

