'''Matsue Gokoku Shrine''' (松江護國神社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] ([[:en:Gokoku shrines|Gokoku Shrine]]) located on the site of [[:en:Matsue Castle|Matsue Castle]] in [[:en:Matsue|Matsue]], [[:en:Shimane Prefecture|Shimane Prefecture]].

== Overview ==
The shrine enshrines over 22,000 spirits of war dead from the former {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|Izumo Province|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izumo Province|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Oki Province|ja|Oki Province|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oki Province|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} who died in national crises after the [[:en:Meiji Restoration|Meiji Restoration]]. Another Gokoku Shrine in the prefecture is {{ill|Hamada Gokoku Shrine|ja|濱田護國神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hamada Gokoku Shrine|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}.

In [[:en:Shōwa era|Showa]] 10 ([[:en:1935|1935]]), the Shimane Prefecture Shokonsha Construction Support Association was organized. In Showa 14 ([[:en:1939|1939]]), it was established and enshrined as Matsue Shokonsha in March, but in April of the same year, due to the reformation of the Shokonsha system, it became Matsue Gokoku Shrine. After [[:en:World War II|World War II]], it was temporarily called Shimane Shrine, but after Japan's sovereignty was restored, the original name was reinstated in Showa 28 ([[:en:1953|1953]]).

On May 10, Showa 40 ([[:en:1965|1965]]), [[:en:Hirohito|Emperor Showa]] and [[:en:Empress Nagako|Empress Kojun]] visited the shrine during the 16th {{ill|National Tree-Planting Festival|lt=National Tree-Planting Festival|lt=National Tree Planting festival|ja|全国植樹祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Tree Planting festival|qq=}}, which was held in the prefecture<ref>{{Cite book |和書 |author={{ill|Takeuchi Tadanori|ja|原武史|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeuchi Tadanori|qq=}} |title=昭和天皇御召列車全記録 |publisher=新潮社 |year=2016-09-30 |page=129 |isbn=978-4-10-320523-4}}</ref>.

