'''Matsue Gokoku Shrine''' (松江護國神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} ({{ill|Gokoku shrines|en|Gokoku shrines|qid=Q1534477|lt=Gokoku Shrine|1=Gokoku Shrines}}) located on the site of {{ill|Matsue Castle|en|Matsue Castle|qid=Q151776|lt=Matsue Castle|1=Matsue Castle}} in {{ill|Matsue|en|Matsue|qid=Q207321|lt=Matsue|1=Matsue}}, {{ill|Shimane Prefecture|en|Shimane Prefecture|qid=Q132751|lt=Shimane Prefecture|1=Shimane Prefecture}}.

== Overview ==
The shrine enshrines over 22,000 spirits of war dead from the former {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|Izumo Province|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izumo Province|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Oki Province|ja|Oki Province|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oki Province|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} who died in national crises after the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|en|Meiji Restoration|qid=Q8707|lt=Meiji Restoration|1=Meiji Restoration}}. Another Gokoku Shrine in the prefecture is {{ill|Hamada Gokoku Shrine|ja|濱田護國神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hamada Gokoku Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Hamada Gokoku Shrine|qid=Q11566232}}.

In {{ill|Shōwa era|en|Shōwa era|qid=Q327567|lt=Showa|1=Shōwa era}} 10 ({{ill|1935|en|1935|qid=Q18658|lt=1935|1=1935}}), the Shimane Prefecture Shokonsha Construction Support Association was organized. In Showa 14 ({{ill|1939|en|1939|qid=Q18639|lt=1939|1=1939}}), it was established and enshrined as Matsue Shokonsha in March, but in April of the same year, due to the reformation of the Shokonsha system, it became Matsue Gokoku Shrine. After {{ill|World War II|en|World War II|qid=Q362|lt=World War II|1=World War II}}, it was temporarily called Shimane Shrine, but after Japan's sovereignty was restored, the original name was reinstated in Showa 28 ({{ill|1953|en|1953|qid=Q18585|lt=1953|1=1953}}).

On May 10, Showa 40 ({{ill|1965|en|1965|qid=Q2650|lt=1965|1=1965}}), {{ill|Hirohito|en|Hirohito|qid=Q34479|lt=Emperor Showa|1=Hirohito}} and {{ill|Empress Nagako|en|Empress Nagako|qid=Q230697|lt=Empress Kojun|1=Empress Nagako}} visited the shrine during the 16th {{ill|National Tree-Planting Festival|lt=National Tree-Planting Festival|lt=National Tree Planting festival|ja|全国植樹祭|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Tree Planting festival|qq=}}, which was held in the prefecture<ref>{{Cite book |和書 |author={{ill|Takeuchi Tadanori|ja|原武史|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeuchi Tadanori|1=Takeshi Hara|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11409676}} |title=昭和天皇御召列車全記録 |publisher=新潮社 |year=2016-09-30 |page=129 |isbn=978-4-10-320523-4}}</ref>.

